cs.IT, cs.NI, cs.SI, cs.CC, cs.MM

Reasoning: 
1. cs.IT (Information Theory) - The paper proposes a new achievable rate region for the Gaussian cognitive many-to-one interference channel using lattice codes and compute-and-forward approach. This falls under the domain of information theory.
2. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) - The paper deals with interference channels, which are a key aspect of wireless networking. The proposed coding scheme can be applied to many-to-one interference channels, which are commonly encountered in wireless networks.
3. cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) - The paper discusses cognitive interference channels, where some users have access to additional information about the messages being transmitted. This is relevant to social and information networks where users may have different levels of knowledge or access to information.
4. cs.CC (Computational Complexity) - The paper uses lattice codes, which are a type of coding scheme that can be efficiently decoded using lattice reduction algorithms. This falls under the domain of computational complexity.
5. cs.MM (Multimedia) - The paper does not directly deal with multimedia, but the proposed coding scheme can be applied to wireless networks that transmit multimedia data.
